Here is how the game is played. Based on your risk aversion profile, you
pick an investment medium that fits that profile. So, if you are risk
adverse, you will pick a low risk investment medium. If you are the direct
opposite, the odds are you will pick a more volatile investment medium. But
regardless of which medium you use, the only difference between the two is
one will likely give you more money when you are ready to retire than the
alternative. But you will still end up with a pot full of money, if you do
it for a long enough period of time, and if you put aside enough money
during that time. But there is a built-in advantage to the high risk
approach, and that is called dollar cost averaging and volatility. An
aggressive growth fund for example will be much more volatile that say an
income fund. But in the early years of your investment period, that is an
advantage, not a disadvantage (but obviously a risky strategy when you get
close to retirement).That is because of a concept called dollar cost
averaging. The more volitity you have when you are dollar cost averaging,
which is what you are doing when you build your retirement nestegg, the more
money you will make and of course the reverse is true, the less volitity you
have, the less money you will make.

