One little thing: shares are more risky than bonds (to take two
examples). This difference does not decrease with your time horizon, but
increase. The longer your investment period, the greater the chance that
companies go bankrupt, etc., i.e. the greater the chance that you lose
your money on your shares. That's why option prices increase with their
time to maturity. This idea that shares really aren't that risky as long
as you hold on to them long enough is also a behavioural finance
fallacy. (By this I mean that it is inconsistent with rational analysis,
but behavioural finance shows why it is tempting for us to believe in it
anyway, the same as the dollar cost averaging above.)

