==================================

Beware of &quot;Juice Pumping&quot;! This is a tactic where a typically smaller
mutual fund picks stocks that have prices that significantly move up as a
result of the fund buying these stocks. If you notice such a fund
bragging about their results, chances are you can only get in by buying at
such artificially high prices that gave them the results they used for
selling you on such a mutual fund.

==================================

Beware of &quot;Window Dressing&quot;. This is a tactic where mutual funds buy
winning stocks so as to report that they owned the winners - but all too
often they bought the winners after they went up although before the end
of the period that had defined reporting requirements.
In addition, the &quot;window dressers&quot; get rid of the losers after the
losers caused losses. This enables the &quot;window dressers&quot; to tell you that
they did not own the losers - but this is only as of close of reporting
period, as opposed to when they incurred the losses by owning the losers.

===================================

Now for more waryness about trying to beat the market: Let me tell
you about psychic ability and &quot;The Force being with me&quot; to require a bit
of luck to do this!

I forget the year, but most of that year Best Buy looked good. Most of
the middle of that year BBY price was around $30. I received a vibe that
I could buy BBY at $24 the following October of that year.

As a result, I bought some BBY at 24-7/8.

At that time and for all too many of the days in the following few
months, I had good vibe reception as to how BBY share price was doing.
Many days I could predict the closing price to $.25 on days when the price
moved $1 or more, at a couple hours before market close with no
non-telepathic contact during trading hours.

And what good did that do me?

I received enough vibes - from &quot;The Herd&quot; on Wall Street!

After I bought 400 shares at 24-7/8, before seeing any share price
after buying them, I felt the downward momentum not stopping after I
bought them. Saw 23-7/8 next day and 22-something a day after that.
And I knew telepatically that this happened before I could get the share
price via ordinary channels, although after my purchase of 300 shares!

BBY continued going down, and I bought 400 shares around $16 apiece.
After that I saw BBY going down to about $8 and then turning up.

I sold my 700 shares of BBY at a following time when doing so greatly
beat the market in a period when the market did well.
So what went wrong? I sold my 700 shares at around $40, and BBY went
into the 50's not much longer afterwards.

My next major stock move was Ford and beat the market doing so.

So what could go wrong? After selling Ford I bought Intel. I sold
Intel close to peak of the NASDAQ bubble. What next? I rebought Intel
after they fell noticeably, betting they were &quot;Blue Chip&quot; enough to not
fall outright through the toilet, and betting on prospects of sales growth
in &quot;emerging nations&quot;. I rebought Intel in steps through their descent
after the NASDAQ bubble, but too soon, as in all-too-early in the NASDAQ
descent that I overestimated there immunity to, and I also underestimated
how bad the NASDAQ descent would be until all of its damage was done. A
good 5 years later the NASDAQ is about 40% of its high over 5 years old,
and I did better than that with Intel but still am in negative territory
from rebuying them during their descent.

Bottom line: Even telepathy and &quot;The Force&quot; won't help you much to beat
the market. Better off just dumping your money into an index fund, and
any extra skills that you wanted to use to &quot;beat the market&quot; you should
use for other purposes.

===================================================

Possible retirement fund strategy to beat the market a little: Use
three Vanguard index funds that are roughly equal thirds of the USA stock
market, namely:

* Index Value (lower price/book-value half of the S&amp;P 500)
* Index Growth (higher price/book-value half of the S&amp;P 500)
* Index Extended (approximates investing in all stocks smaller
than those in S&amp;P 500)

Every paycheck or every month, put an equal amount of money into each.
This results not only buying more shares when the price is low, but also
more shares of what is running low.

In a non-retirement account, I advise buying Vanguard &quot;Index Total&quot;. In
a taxable account, this fund has the advantage of not selling shares (and
causing you taxable capital gains distributions) - this fund can only
cause you a taxable capital gain prior to you selling by owning shares
that get destroyed at a gain, and that can't be much.

Vanguard has another stock fund designed for tax advantage, and that one
is VTMF (&quot;Vanguard Tax Managed Fund&quot;) &quot;Capital Appreciation&quot; - and that
one buys stocks in roughly the lower dividend-yield half of the largest
roughly 1,000 USA stocks, and does not sell at price above *zero* except
should the fund have a cash outflow due to redemptions exceeding
contributions. What you gain in this fund in a taxable account is mostly
tax-deferred to when you cash out.
However, I see this fund having only a minor tax advantage over Vanguard
&quot;Index Total&quot;, and I see &quot;Index Total&quot; having an advantage of mostly (but
not always - BEWARE!) less volatility than &quot;VTMF Capital Appreciation&quot;,
which concentrates to large-cap and largish-midcap &quot;growth stocks&quot;.

If you are in a lower tax bracket but have money to put into a mutual
fund whose realized gains and dividends you have to pay taxes on
year-by-year, then whatever advantage to you of &quot;VTMF Capital Apprecian&quot;
over &quot;Index Total&quot; is decreased - may as well go for the better
diversification of &quot;Index Total&quot;.

